org.toolboxframework

Class Toolbox

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.toolboxframework.Toolbox

  • public class Toolbox
extends java.lang.Object
    The Toolbox class provides ways to add and remove tools from the toolbox, as well as to know whether or not the toolbox contains a tool.

    Typical usage could include using the addTool(Object, String) method to add tools to the toolbox before constructing instances of classes which use the UseTool field annotation. However, scanning for tools using one of the methods provided in ToolScanner is usually a more convenient way to populate the toolbox with tools. Therefore, there is rarely ever a need to write code that makes calls to the methods in this class.

    See Also:
    ToolScanner

      • getTool

        public static <T> T getTool(java.lang.Class<T> requiredType,
                            java.lang.String fallbackName)
        Return the tool that uniquely matches the given object type, or, if there are multiple tools in the toolbox that match the given object type, return the one with the given fallback name.
        Parameters:
        requiredType - type the tool must match (can be an interface or superclass of the actual class)
        fallbackName - the tool name to fallback on in case the tool cannot be resolved by type
        Returns:
        the tool with the given type, if unique, or the tool with the given name and type
        Throws:
        NoUniqueToolForTypeException - if the toolbox contains more than one tool of the given type and none of the names of those tools equal the provided fallback name
        ToolNotFoundException - if the toolbox does not contain a tool that matches the given object type

      • getTool

        public static <T> T getTool(java.lang.String toolName,
                            java.lang.Class<T> requiredType)
        Return the tool with the given name and type.

        Behaves the same as getTool(String), but provides a measure of type safety by throwing a ToolNotOfRequiredTypeException if the tool is not of the required type. This means that ClassCastException can't be thrown on casting the result correctly, as can happen with getTool(String).

        Parameters:
        toolName - the name of the tool to query
        requiredType - type the tool must match (can be an interface or superclass of the actual class)
        Returns:
        the tool with the given name and type
        Throws:
        ToolNotFoundException - if the toolbox does not contain a tool with the given name
        ToolNotOfRequiredTypeException - if the tool is not of the required type
